ns, which is wrong. For example, a player who has `b[i] > b[max_a_idx]` but `a[i] < a[max_b_idx]` would be marked as winner but can't beat the max-B player.\n\n**Test case to trigger the bug:**\n```\n1\n3\n1 3 2\n3 1 2\n```\n- max_a_idx = 1 (a=3), max_b_idx = 0 (b=3)\n- Player 2: b[2]=2 > b[max_a_idx]=b[1]=1 \u2192 marked \"1\", but a[2]=2 < a[max_b_idx]=a[0]=1? No, a[0]=1, a[2]=2 > 1, so condition 4 also holds. Bad example.\n\nTry:\n```\n1\n4\n10 20 15 5\n5 10 20 15\n```\n- max_a_idx=1 (a=20), max_b_idx=2 (b=20)\n- Player 3 (0-indexed): a[3]=5, b[3]=15. b[3]=15 > b[max_a_idx]=b[1]=10 \u2192 \"1\". But a[3]=5 < a[max_b_idx]=a[2]=15, so can't beat player 2 on map A, and b[3]=15 < 20 so can't beat on map B. Player 3 cannot win, but code says \"1\".\n\n```json\n{\"verdict\": \"FAIL\", \"bugs\": [{\"description\": \"Conditions b[i] > b[max_a_idx] and a[i] > a[max_b_idx] should be combined with AND (not OR) for players who aren't map champions. A player who can beat the map-A champion on map B but cannot beat the map-B champion on either map is incorrectly marked as a potential winner.\", \"line\": 12, \"severity\": \"critical\", \"triggering_input\": \"1\\n4\\n10 20 15 5\\n5 10 20 15\"}]}\n```",
